WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.520
So, getting to the question. Does this look familiar? Wait for it. It's coming. One more

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:24.760
second. There we go. So, as we just saw, small plots lead to a bad user experience. I'm Ryszard

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:31.799
Szymanski, I'm an R Shiny developer at Epsilon, and this is my worst nightmare. So, bottlenecks

00:00:31.799 --> 00:00:37.439
can occur in different parts of the process, which are, you first start with data preparation,

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:41.520
so let's say you fetch data from your database, you do some aggregations before you start

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:45.799
working on your plot, then you define your plot in R using your favorite library like,

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:51.959
I don't know, Plotly or HRS4R, and later on, all of the plot-related data and settings

00:00:51.959 --> 00:00:58.680
get sent to the browser where your plots get rendered. And what I've discovered, that

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:03.560
there are three main root causes of bottlenecks happening in the plot rendering process, the

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:08.599
first one being an inefficient data preparation process. So, let's say you want to visualize

00:01:08.599 --> 00:01:13.639
your home budget data, and you want to visualize it in the form of a box plot. This is how

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:18.760
you would go about it in Plotly, and it makes it super convenient to do in R, so you plug

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:25.800
in your data set, you pick your variable, and you pick your plot type. But, let's focus

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:31.040
on our first line right here, so how do we prepare the data? So, that code here might

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:35.639
work very well for small data, let's say you just have a couple of rows, but as your data

00:01:35.639 --> 00:01:41.720
gets bigger, you're essentially fetching all of your data sets, all of your data set, into

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:45.800
the memory of your process, just to create a box plot. So if you have millions of rows

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:50.120
in the database, that can be pretty inefficient. But let's go back to our box plot. To plot

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:54.879
a box plot, you just need five values, the minimum value, the lower quartile, the median,

00:01:54.879 --> 00:01:58.879
the upper quartile, and the maximum value. So what if instead of fetching millions of

00:01:58.879 --> 00:02:03.720
rows, you would just calculate those five values on the database site, and plug it into

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:10.360
your Plotly function like this. Sometimes we also try to show too much, and it can manifest

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:15.320
itself in different ways. For example, let's go back to our millions of points, and let's

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:19.960
say we're using a scatter plot to visualize it. Rendering millions of points can take

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:25.720
a while. Perhaps you can convey the same type of information using a different plot. Again,

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:29.320
let's go back to the example of the box plot, where you can just fetch five values and show

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:34.839
perhaps the similar information you want to convey. Also, when you're creating a dashboard,

00:02:34.839 --> 00:02:41.160
it might be very tempting to put a lot of plots in your dashboard, but the reality is

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:45.960
users rarely are able to focus on all of them at once. And rendering six plots might

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:50.000
take a while, so why not instead just show one plot and provide controls for your users

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:56.679
to switch between each type of plot to make it faster. We sometimes also use our plotting

00:02:56.679 --> 00:03:02.199
libraries inefficiently. So a lot of libraries provide convenience functions like toWebGL

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:07.240
in Plotly or BoostMode in HighCharter, which leverage a technology called WebGL, which

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:13.399
makes use of your GPU to render your plot in the browser faster. And in some cases,

00:03:13.399 --> 00:03:17.559
there are some available options, like for example, the HighCharter RJSON option in the

00:03:17.559 --> 00:03:22.919
HighCharter package. And HighCharter by default uses a package called JSON Lite to prepare

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:28.160
data and settings for the browser, and as your data gets larger, it can get a bit slow.

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:34.759
And RJSON is a bit more efficient, and some users have reported a 25x speed increase while

00:03:34.759 --> 00:03:39.880
switching to RJSON. All right, thank you. That will be it for me, and if you have any

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:43.639
questions, you can post them on the slide deck that's been mentioned, or if you want

00:03:43.639 --> 00:03:45.440
to talk to me, you can find me at the AppState booth.

